content: Is it gonna be updated to the New National Registry & Heart Association Standards
replyContent: The app has been updated to reflect the 2015 AHA guidelines.

content: Answers to questions are outdated and inaccurate. Not worth the 10 dollars to get the wrong information
replyContent: The questions and answer are all up to date as of the current education standards and the 2015 AHA Guidelines.  If you feel there is a question that is not accurate, please contact Limmer Creative support so that we can look into the issue.

content: This app has helped me pass nremt.

Highly recommended as someone who has passed national registry at the paramedic level. The questions are high quality and there are good explanations for them so you learn from each question. This turned out to be the best bank of test questions when preparing for national registry.
Good questions and rationalization

There's a question in the first exam (#35 if its always the same) that shows all signs of CHF/right sided heart failure. The question is treatment based. In the rational it states a concern for ACS over CHF. What is the logic of concern for ACS, especially over CHF?           Either way, love this app. It's been a huge help thus far.
Lately I have been having an issue with the app saying questions were unanswered or the app fails to record any questions as answered
This was my "bathroom buddy." I studied these questions constantly during my internship to get ready for registry. Passed first attempt. Worth the price.
Had let my National card lapse and this app was extremely helpful to recert.
Very helpful, passed my nremt and state exams
Excellent source to study from
Definitely challenging and gives reasons why something is wrong or right that you chose.
Good review for NRENT P exam

In the pharmacology section the question of what drug would be most beneficial to a patient in CHF, I feel should be removed. Aren't the benefits of furosemide prehospitally are marginal at best when compared to CPAP? Could readapt this question in airway or medical? Cpap is by far more beneficial and less intrusive.   Overall, this and it's accompanied apps are outstanding. Thank you for your time.
replyContent: You are correct that CPAP is making its way into EMS protocols quite vigorously now--as furosemide moves out. We try to carefully monitor issues like this in practice, & in testing, where changes happen a bit slower. Our apps must meet a wide range of protocols, exams & clinical concepts. We will look into this. Thank you for your kind words.
